[4] Research
- Tue 9 Jul 2019.
[The Lancet Infectious Diseases, abridged, edited]
http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S1473-3099(19)30291-9

Citation: McMullan LK, Flint M, Chakrabarti A, et al. Characterisation of infectious Ebola virus from the ongoing outbreak to guide response activities in the Democratic Republic of the Congo: a phylogenetic and in vitro analysis. Lancet Infect Dis 2019 http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S1473-3099(19)30291-9.

Background: The aim of this study was to test the efficacy of candidate therapies and diagnostic tests with the outbreak strain Ituri Ebola virus. Lacking a virus isolate from this outbreak, a recombinant Ituri Ebola virus was compared with a similarly engineered Makona virus from the 2013-16 outbreak.

Methods: Using Ebola virus sequences provided by organisations in DR Congo and a reverse genetics system, we generated an authentic Ebola virus from the ongoing outbreak in Ituri and North Kivu provinces. To relate this virus to other Ebola viruses in DR Congo, we did a phylogenetic analysis of representative complete Ebola virus genome sequences from previous outbreaks. We evaluated experimental therapies being tested in clinical trials in DR Congo, including remdesivir and ZMapp monoclonal antibodies, for their ability to inhibit the growth of infectious Ituri Ebola virus in cell culture. We also tested diagnostic assays for detection of the Ituri Ebola virus sequence.

Findings: The phylogenetic analysis of whole-genome sequences from each Ebola virus outbreak suggests there are at least 2 Ebola virus strains in DR Congo, which have independently crossed into the human population. The Ituri Ebola strain initially grew slower than the Makona strain, yet reached similar mean yields of 3 [times] 10(7) 50% tissue culture infectious dose by 72 h infection in Huh-7 cells. Ituri Ebola virus was similar to Makona in its susceptibility to inhibition by remdesivir and to neutralisation by monoclonal antibodies from ZMapp and other monoclonal antibodies. Remdesivir inhibited Ituri Ebola virus at a 50% effective concentration (EC50) of 12 nM (with a selectivity index of 303) and Makona Ebola virus at 13 nM (with a selectivity index of 279). The ZMapp monoclonal antibodies 2G4 and 4G7 neutralised Ituri Ebola virus with a mean EC50 of 0.24 microgram/mL and 0.48 microgram/mL, and Makona Ebola virus with a mean EC50 of 0.45 microgram/mL and 0.2 microgram/mL. The Xpert Ebola and US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention real-time RT-qPCR diagnostic assays detected Ituri and Makona Ebola virus sequences with similar sensitivities and efficiencies, despite primer site binding mismatches in the Ituri Ebola virus.

- Tue 9 Jul 2019. Comment
[The Lancet Infectious Diseases 2019, abridged, edited]
https://doi.org/10.1016/S1473-3099(19)30346-9

Citation: Cross RW, Geisbert TW. Use of reverse genetics to inform Ebola outbreak responses. Lancet Infect Dis 2019 https://doi.org/10.1016/S1473-3099(19)30346-9.

In The Lancet Infectious Diseases, Laura K. McMullan and colleagues present the 1st occasion in which reverse genetics technology has been used to generate an Ebola virus isolate using sequence information from an ongoing filovirus outbreak where isolates were not readily available. The engineered isolate contains a fluorescent reporter protein (Zoanthus green fluorescent protein) that allows virus growth to be quantified by measuring fluorescence in infected cells. McMullan and colleagues assessed the efficacy of investigational therapies against Ebola virus disease and the sensitivity of diagnostic assays approved for emergency use in the 2018 outbreak. Importantly, the authors showed that investigational therapies being tested in clinical trials in DR Congo (including remdesivir and ZMapp monoclonal antibodies) are effective against viruses known to be circulating in the outbreak. The Ebola diagnostic assays approved for emergency use by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and WHO detected Ituri Ebola virus with high sensitivity despite primer site binding mismatches.

Efficacy [of countermeasures] is dependent on the availability of information about the exact virus isolate responsible for the outbreak. Although heroic efforts have been made by Congolese scientists and those with the Institut National de Recherche Biomedicale (Kinshasa, DR Congo) and US Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases (Fort Detrick, MD) to ensure sequence information is available to the scientific community, only predictive inferences can be made about the efficacy of any medical countermeasure used in the current outbreak.

The findings by McMullan and colleagues support the continued testing of investigational therapies against Ebola virus disease in the ongoing outbreak, and have renewed confidence in the Ebola assays approved for emergency use. Further work is needed to characterise host responses to infection with this engineered Ebola isolate compared with other Ebola isolates. In vivo verification of antiviral and vaccine candidate efficacy is of equal importance to strengthen global confidence in new medical countermeasures and make the necessary refinements.

